{"title_page": "Gordhan Zadafia", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Gordhan Zadafia\n| order = Minister for Home and Security and Police Housing (Independent Charge)  In Tenth Gujarat Legislative Assembly, 1998-2002\n| party = [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1954|6|20|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Gariadhar]], Gujarat, India\n| nationality = Indian\n| spouse = Leelaben\n| education = B.Sc., M.P.A. (Master of Public Administration), Diploma in Marketing Management\n| religion = Hinduism\n}}\n\n'''Gordhan Zadafia''' (born 20 June 1954) is an Indian politician from [[Gujarat]], [[India]]. He was a leader in [[Vishva Hindu Parishad]] (VHP) for 15 years before joining [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP).\n\nHe served as the General Secretary of BJP in [[Ahmedabad]] city and was elected twice as a member of the [[Gujarat Legislative Assembly]] during 1995\u201397 and 1998\u20132002. He was a Minister of State for Home and Security and Police Housing (Independent Charge) during 2001\u20132002 in the state Government of Gujarat led by [[Narendra Modi]].<ref>\n{{cite web |url=http://www.gujaratassembly.gov.in/epahmedabad.htm#SHRI_GORDHANBHAI_PRAGJIBHAI_ZADAFIA |title=Gujarat Assembly membership records}}</ref>\n\nHe was accused of involvement in the [[2002 Gujarat riots]]. Following a break with Narendra Modi after 2002, he pursued other political parties, competing against BJP, but eventually rejoined BJP in 2014.\n\n== Political career ==\n\nZadafia was a close associate of the VHP chief [[Praveen Togadia]] in Gujarat unit of VHP. He is reported to have been inducted as a Minister in the Modi cabinet as a sop to the latter for his support of Modi's chief ministership.{{sfn|Marino|2014|p=165}} Zadafia is accused of involvement in the [[2002 Gujarat riots]] by posting police officers sympathetic to VHP in strategic positions and accused of helping unleash violence.<ref name=Togadia>{{cite news |title=History of how Modi and Togadia fell out |newspaper=Times of India |date=22 Apr 2014 |accessdate=26 Aug 2014 |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/news/History-of-how-Modi-and-Togadia-fell-out/articleshow/34068095.cms? |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140909120427/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/news/History-of-how-Modi-and-Togadia-fell-out/articleshow/34068095.cms |archive-date=9 September 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He transferred police officers such as [[Rahul Sharma (Gujarat police)|Rahul Sharma]].{{sfn|Bunsha|2014}} On his orders, police raided refugee camps claiming that they housed rioters.{{sfn|Bunsha|2014}}<ref name=survivors>{{cite news |author=Mari Marcel Thekaekara |title=The Survivors Speak |newspaper=The Hindu |date=12 May 2002 |accessdate=28 Aug 2014 |url=http://www.thehindu.com/2002/05/12/stories/2002051200801100.htm}}</ref>\n\nAfter the December 2002 elections, [[Narendra Modi]] dropped him from the cabinet to signal a break with BJP.{{sfn|Marino|2014|p=165}} Zadafia subsequently floated a new political party, [[Mahagujarat Janata Party]] (MJP) during the 2007 assembly elections in Gujarat, later merged into the [[Gujarat Parivartan Party]] of former chief minister [[Keshubhai Patel]].\n\nDuring the 2012 assembly elections, Togadia and VHP activists campaigned hard for the [[Gujarat Parivartan Party]] against the BJP. Despite all efforts, Zadafia and his team lost the 2012 elections. The VHP support for Zadafia ended up strengthening [[Narendra Modi]]'s anti-hardline Hindutva image.<ref name=cutdown>{{cite news |author=Sanjay Singh |title=How Modi cut Togadia down to size in Gujarat |newspaper=Firstpost |date=2 Apr 2013 |accessdate=28 Aug 2014 |url=http://www.firstpost.com/politics/how-modi-cut-togadia-down-to-size-in-gujarat-682365.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140815121746/http://www.firstpost.com/politics/how-modi-cut-togadia-down-to-size-in-gujarat-682365.html |archive-date=15 August 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Supreme Court of India|Supreme Court]]-appointed Special Investigation Team (SIT) questioned Zadafia thrice regarding his role in the 2002 riots. Following reports that SIT had found evidence against him and senior police officers, it was reported that Zadafia was inclined to testify against Modi. Following pressure from RSS leaders, Zadafia refrained from such a move.<ref name=RSS>{{cite news |title=RSS telling Zadaphia not to testify against Modi: Sources |newspaper=Times of India |date=5 Sep 2010 |accessdate=28 Aug 2014 |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/RSS-telling-Zadaphia-not-to-testify-against-Modi-Sources/articleshow/6493649.cms |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141201032539/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/RSS-telling-Zadaphia-not-to-testify-against-Modi-Sources/articleshow/6493649.cms |archive-date=1 December 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 24 February 2014, Zadafia rejoined the BJP and merged  [[Gujarat Parivartan Party]] into it.<ref name=back>{{cite news |title=Gordhan Zadaphia back in BJP; in-house threat for Modi is over |newspaper=Firstpost |date=24 Feb 2014 |accessdate=28 Aug 2014 |url=http://www.firstpost.com/politics/gordhan-zadaphia-back-in-bjp-in-house-threat-for-modi-is-over-1406657.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301205409/http://www.firstpost.com/politics/gordhan-zadaphia-back-in-bjp-in-house-threat-for-modi-is-over-1406657.html |archive-date=1 March 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bunsha|first=Dionne|title=Scarred: Experiment's With Violence In Gujarat|year=2005|publisher=Penguin|isbn=978-0-14-400076-0|ref={{sfnref|Bunsha|2005}}}}\n* {{cite book|last=Marino |first=Andy |title=Narendra Modi: A Political Biography |year=2014 |publisher=HarperCollins Publishers India |isbn=978-93-5136-217-3 |ref={{sfnref|Marino|2014}}}}\n* {{cite news |last=Jose |first=Vinod K |title=The Emperor Uncrowned: The rise of Narendra Modi |newspaper=Caravan |date=1 March 2012 |accessdate=28 Aug 2014 |url=http://caravanmagazine.in/reportage/emperor-uncrowned?page=0,0 |ref={{sfnref|Jose|2012}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Sangh Parivar}}\n{{Bharatiya Janata Party}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zadafia, Gordhan}}\n[[Category:Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh members]]\n[[Category:Vishva Hindu Parishad members]]\n[[Category:2002 Gujarat riots]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Ahmedabad]]\n[[Category:Members of the Gujarat Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian politicians]]\n[[Category:Bharatiya Janata Party politicians from Gujarat]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Gordhan Zadafia\n| order = Minister for Home and Security and Police Housing (Independent Charge)  In Tenth Gujarat Legislative Assembly, 1998-2002\n| party = [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1954|6|20|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Gariadhar]], Gujarat, India\n| nationality = Indian\n| spouse = Leelaben\n| education = B.Sc., M.P.A. (Master of Public Administration), Diploma in Marketing Management\n| religion = Hinduism\n}}\n\n'''Gordhan Zadafia''' (born 20 June 1954) is an Indian politician from [[Gujarat]], [[India]]. He was a leader in [[Vishva Hindu Parishad]] (VHP) for 15 years before joining [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP).\n\nHe served as the General Secretary of BJP in [[Ahmedabad]] city and was elected twice as a member of the [[Gujarat Legislative Assembly]] during 1995\u201397 and 1998\u20132002. He was a Minister of State for Home and Security and Police Housing (Independent Charge) during 2001-2002 in the state Government of Gujarat led by [[Narendra Modi]].<ref>\n{{cite web |url=http://www.gujaratassembly.gov.in/epahmedabad.htm#SHRI_GORDHANBHAI_PRAGJIBHAI_ZADAFIA |title=Gujarat Assembly membership records}}</ref>\n\nHe was accused of involvement in the [[2002 Gujarat riots]]. Following a break with Narendra Modi after 2002, he pursued other political parties, competing against BJP, but eventually rejoined BJP in 2014.\n\n== Political career ==\n\nZadafia was a close associate of the VHP chief [[Praveen Togadia]] in Gujarat unit of VHP. He is reported to have been inducted as a Minister in the Modi cabinet as a sop to the latter for his support of Modi's chief ministership.{{sfn|Marino|2014|p=165}} Zadafia is accused of involvement in the [[2002 Gujarat riots]] by posting police officers sympathetic to VHP in strategic positions and accused of helping unleash violence.<ref name=Togadia>{{cite news |title=History of how Modi and Togadia fell out |newspaper=Times of India |date=22 Apr 2014 |accessdate=26 Aug 2014 |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/news/History-of-how-Modi-and-Togadia-fell-out/articleshow/34068095.cms? |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140909120427/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/news/History-of-how-Modi-and-Togadia-fell-out/articleshow/34068095.cms |archive-date=9 September 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He transferred police officers such as [[Rahul Sharma (Gujarat police)|Rahul Sharma]].{{sfn|Bunsha|2014}} On his orders, police raided refugee camps claiming that they housed rioters.{{sfn|Bunsha|2014}}<ref name=survivors>{{cite news |author=Mari Marcel Thekaekara |title=The Survivors Speak |newspaper=The Hindu |date=12 May 2002 |accessdate=28 Aug 2014 |url=http://www.thehindu.com/2002/05/12/stories/2002051200801100.htm}}</ref>\n\nAfter the December 2002 elections, [[Narendra Modi]] dropped him from the cabinet to signal a break with BJP.{{sfn|Marino|2014|p=165}} Zadafia subsequently floated a new political party, [[Mahagujarat Janata Party]] (MJP) during the 2007 assembly elections in Gujarat, later merged into the [[Gujarat Parivartan Party]] of former chief minister [[Keshubhai Patel]].\n\nDuring the 2012 assembly elections, Togadia and VHP activists campaigned hard for the [[Gujarat Parivartan Party]] against the BJP. Despite all efforts, Zadafia and his team lost the 2012 elections. The VHP support for Zadafia ended up strengthening [[Narendra Modi]]'s anti-hardline Hindutva image.<ref name=cutdown>{{cite news |author=Sanjay Singh |title=How Modi cut Togadia down to size in Gujarat |newspaper=Firstpost |date=2 Apr 2013 |accessdate=28 Aug 2014 |url=http://www.firstpost.com/politics/how-modi-cut-togadia-down-to-size-in-gujarat-682365.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140815121746/http://www.firstpost.com/politics/how-modi-cut-togadia-down-to-size-in-gujarat-682365.html |archive-date=15 August 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Supreme Court of India|Supreme Court]]-appointed Special Investigation Team (SIT) questioned Zadafia thrice regarding his role in the 2002 riots. Following reports that SIT had found evidence against him and senior police officers, it was reported that Zadafia was inclined to testify against Modi. Following pressure from RSS leaders, Zadafia refrained from such a move.<ref name=RSS>{{cite news |title=RSS telling Zadaphia not to testify against Modi: Sources |newspaper=Times of India |date=5 Sep 2010 |accessdate=28 Aug 2014 |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/RSS-telling-Zadaphia-not-to-testify-against-Modi-Sources/articleshow/6493649.cms |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141201032539/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/RSS-telling-Zadaphia-not-to-testify-against-Modi-Sources/articleshow/6493649.cms |archive-date=1 December 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 24 February 2014, Zadafia rejoined the BJP and merged  [[Gujarat Parivartan Party]] into it.<ref name=back>{{cite news |title=Gordhan Zadaphia back in BJP; in-house threat for Modi is over |newspaper=Firstpost |date=24 Feb 2014 |accessdate=28 Aug 2014 |url=http://www.firstpost.com/politics/gordhan-zadaphia-back-in-bjp-in-house-threat-for-modi-is-over-1406657.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301205409/http://www.firstpost.com/politics/gordhan-zadaphia-back-in-bjp-in-house-threat-for-modi-is-over-1406657.html |archive-date=1 March 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bunsha|first=Dionne|title=Scarred: Experiment's With Violence In Gujarat|year=2005|publisher=Penguin|isbn=978-0-14-400076-0|ref={{sfnref|Bunsha|2005}}}}\n* {{cite book|last=Marino |first=Andy |title=Narendra Modi: A Political Biography |year=2014 |publisher=HarperCollins Publishers India |isbn=978-93-5136-217-3 |ref={{sfnref|Marino|2014}}}}\n* {{cite news |last=Jose |first=Vinod K |title=The Emperor Uncrowned: The rise of Narendra Modi |newspaper=Caravan |date=1 March 2012 |accessdate=28 Aug 2014 |url=http://caravanmagazine.in/reportage/emperor-uncrowned?page=0,0 |ref={{sfnref|Jose|2012}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Sangh Parivar}}\n{{Bharatiya Janata Party}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zadafia, Gordhan}}\n[[Category:Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh members]]\n[[Category:Vishva Hindu Parishad members]]\n[[Category:2002 Gujarat riots]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Ahmedabad]]\n[[Category:Members of the Gujarat Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian politicians]]\n[[Category:Bharatiya Janata Party politicians from Gujarat]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up,typo(s) fixed: 2001-2002 \u2192 2001\u20132002", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gordhan_Zadafia"}
{"title_page": "Pham Quang Khiem", "text_new": "<!-- Important, do not remove this line before article has been created. -->\n{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Pham Quang Khiem\n| image         = KhiemQPham.jpg\n| caption       = Lt. Pham Q. Khiem, was pilot of C-130A \"Saigon Lady\"\n| birth_date    = December 27, 1946\n| birth_place   = V\u0129nh-Long, Vietnam\n| allegiance    = {{flag|South Vietnam}}\n| branch        = {{Air force|South Vietnam}}\n| serviceyears  = 1969-1975\n| rank          = First Lieutenant\n| unit          = 435th Transport Squadron\n| battles       = Vietnam War\n| spouse        = Ngoc-My Tran (m. 1972)\n| children      = 3\n| laterwork     = Airline Pilot\n}}\n\nPham Quang Khiem (born December 27, 1946) was a First Lieutenant and Co-Pilot in the [[South Vietnam Air Force]] (VNAF) during the [[Vietnam War]]. Khiem was a cargo pilot with the 53rd Tactical Wing of the 5th Air Division stationed at [[Tan Son Nhut Air Base|Tan Son Nhut]]. Khiem flew several missions into communists gained [[Pleiku Air Base|Pleiku]] in hopes to rescue VNAF personnel. On 03 April 1975, Khiem organized a plan to steal a C-130a and gather 53 people to rescue them from the communist [[North Vietnam|North Vietnamese]]. Later, Khiem became a pilot for [[Piedmont Airlines (1948\u20131989)|Piedmont Airlines]] until 2006.\n\n== Early Life ==\n[[File:Pham_Family_1960.jpg|alt=|left|thumb|190x190px|Pham family in 1960.]]\nPham Quang Khiem was born on December 27, 1946, in [[V\u0129nh Long|V\u0129nh-Long, Vietnam]]. Khiem had ten siblings (five boys and five girls) and all of his brothers were in the military. Three of them were in the VNAF and one in the [[Army of the Republic of Vietnam|ARVN]]. Khiem got married on June 8, 1972, to Ngoc-My Tran. Together they had three children: two in South Vietnam and one in the [[United States|United States of America]].\n\n== Early Career ==\n[[File:Pham_Quang_Khiem_at_Lockbourne_AFB.jpg|alt=|left|thumb|195x195px|Pham Quang Khiem at Lockbourne AFB]]\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://t28trojanfoundation.com/vnaf.html|title=VNAF|website=Helen Murphy|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>In November 1969, Khiem went to [[Lackland Air Force Base|Lackland AFB]] to learn [[English language|English]] as a VNAF air cadet. At [[Randolph Air Force Base|Randolph AFB]], he earned his basic pilot training, then moved on to [[Keesler Air Force Base|Keesler AFB]], where he flew the [[T-28 Trojan]].\u00a0Khiem also trained at [[Lockbourne AFB]] from October-December of 1970. Eventually, he was designated to fly transport aircraft and was pilot-in-command of [[C-123K]] aircraft before moving up to the 53rd Tactical Wing, 435th Transport Squadron as a [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules|C-130A]] pilot. \n\n\n\n\n=== Hard Landing ===\n[[File:PQK Tough Landing.jpg|thumb|Pham Quang Khiem in front of the C-123K after the crash landing]]\nOn January 24, 1971, Pham Quang Khiem nearly died almost ending his flight career before it started.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vnafmamn.com/hall-offame/amazing_story.html|title=VNAF \"amazing story\"|website=vnafmamn.com|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> After a year of training in the states, Khiem's group was sent to [[Phan Rang Air Base|Phan-Rang AFB]] by the VNAF to start \"In Country Training\" with the [[United States Air Force|USAF]] on a [[C-123K]]. Khiem was assigned to fly with 1LT. Minh and their American Instructor, Cpt. John Mastronardi. Minh was the Aircraft Commander in the left seat and in the right, Khiem switched with Captain Mastronardi to execute co-pilot duties. One day, they had an assignment to transfer 48 of 175-millimeter high explosive bullet heads from [[Bien Hoa Air Base|Bien-Hoa Air Base]] to a US firebase 113 kilometers north near the [[Cambodia|Cambodian]] border. They had to land into an isolated area for a safe distance from any airport facilities since they carried high explosive material. They landed on the short dirt strip, [[B\u00f9 Gia M\u1eadp District|B\u00f9 Gia M\u1eadp]] Air Strip (aka Djamap). The runway was 3000' on top of a 1620' hill. Co-Pilots (in this training) weren't allowed to make any landing on any runway shorter than 3600'. Minh was supposed to handle this flight, but Captain Mastronardi kept Khiem in the right seat believing he could handle the landing after previous successful landings. Khiem was a young pilot and didn't know the difference between a short runway and a long one. It was a hostile area so they had to come in high and drop fast. They came down to 2000' at 78 knots and when the [[C-123K]] was about 20 feet in the air crossing the end of the runway Khiem decided to cut the power to idle causing the aircraft to drop touching down extremely hard. The left main landing gear fell into the belly wrecking the wheel and scratched all the red dirt on the runway skyrocketing it into the cockpit. Khiem and Minh couldn't see anything in front of them. Captain Mastronardi immediately reversed the right engine, bringing the aircraft back stopping the aircraft. If Captain Mastronardi had not stop the aircraft, the whole aircraft may have run off the dirt strip dropping hundreds of yards exploding on the side of the hill.\n\n== End of the War ==\nAt the end of March 1975, the North Vietnamese had already taken half of South Vietnam. Citizens were fleeing as well as soldiers creating chaos throughout the country. Both civilians and officers were hitching military aircraft to escape the North Vietnamese. At the end of March of 1975, the [[North Vietnamese army|NVA]] was pushing towards the coast to strike [[Qui Nh\u01a1n]], [[Tuy H\u00f2a]], and [[Nha Trang]]. \n\n=== Pleiku ===\n[[File:North Vietnamese Gains in the last week of March of '75.jpg|thumb|249x249px|North Vietnamese Gains in the last week of March of '75]]\n<ref>{{Cite book|last=Snepp|first=Frank|title=Decent Interval|publisher=Random House|year=1977|isbn=0-394-40743-1|location=New York, United States|pages=234}}</ref> In the north of South Vietnam, the only remaining government enclave was [[Da Nang]]. <ref>{{Cite book|last=Drendel|first=Lou|title=Air War over Southeast Asia|publisher=squadron/signal|year=1984|isbn=0-89747-148-2|location=1115 Crowley Dr., Carrolton, TX|pages=65}}</ref> Khiem flew three missions into and out of [[Pleiku]], evacuating the families of VNAF personnel. The civil population of Pleiku learned of the evacuation and stormed the [[Pleiku Air Base|airport]]. This forced five C-130's en route from Saigon to turn around before their airlifts were complete. Some C-130's flew bombing missions to destroy the aircraft left behind. They were loaded with 55-gallon drums of [[napalm]], then dropped on VNAF aircraft abandoned on the ramps.\n\n=== Da Nang ===\n28 March 1975, Khiem flew one of the last missions to [[Da Nang Air Base|Da Nang]] at 11:00 pm, the night before its loss. When he landed and taxied to the ramp, an [[Army of the Republic of Vietnam|ARVN]] major jumped into the aircraft to assure himself of a seat. Khiem knew that the thousands of people in the terminal would rush the airplane after seeing this, so Khiem kicked him off. Khiem was a First Lieutenant, and the aircraft commander was searching the terminal for his family. But, the ramp was filled with refugees almost immediately anyway. Around 20,000 pounds of cargo on board, so Khiem yelled at them to offload first. The crowd was too chaotic, so Khiem told the [[loadmaster]] to do unloading and loading through the ramp in the back of the C-130. Once finished, people rushed onto the aircraft. Khiem started the engines, scattering many, allowing Khiem to taxi out.\n\nAs they taxied, the loadmaster yelled at Khiem through the intercom saying he couldn't close the ramp because people were on it. Khiem hit the brakes jamming the refugees in tight allowing the ramp to close. At the end of the runway, an MP (Military Police) in a truck had his family in it, blocking the taxiway and pointing his M-16 at the cockpit.  He motioned to let his family on board. Khiem motioned him to move the truck so he could line up on the runway. Khiem backed up, lined up and took off without the MP. Khiem offloaded at [[Tan Son Nhut Air Base|Tan Son Nhut]] and did a headcount of 350 people. C-130's are maximized to carry 92 passengers but Khiem fit almost four times that amount. \n\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://airandspace.si.edu/collection-objects/lockheed-c-130a-45-lm-hercules|title=Lockheed C-130a 45 lm Hercules|last=|first=|date=|website=Smithsonian National Air and Space Museum|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=7 April 2020|quote=\"That flight and the panic that Lt. Khiem saw in Da Nang caused him to consider that if this was likely to happen in Saigon, he would steal a C-130 and get his own family out.\"}}</ref>That mission was the turning point for Khiem. He knew if the chaos reaches Saigon he had to get his family out of Vietnam for good.\n\n=== Nha Trang ===\n31 March 1975, Khiem flew several missions in the evacuation of [[Nha Trang]]. The following day [[Qui Nh\u01a1n]], South Vietnam's third-largest city was captured by the North Vietnamese. The next target for the North Vietnamese was [[Nha Trang Air Base|Nha Trang]]. Khiem just made it just like he did in Da Nang.\n\n== Flight To Freedom ==\n2 April 1975, Khiem caught a ride on a C-130 \"bladder bird\" into [[Phan Rang Air Base|Phan Rang]], in hopes to pinpoint his younger brother, who was an airman there.\u00a0Khiem wanted to take him back to [[Saigon]] to be with the rest of their family.\u00a0Khiem couldn't find hi, so left without him. On the way back to Saigon, Khiem thought if Phan Rang is lost, then\u00a0the communists will come to Saigon. Khiem started to devise a plan to escape South Vietnam with his family. Khiem heard that [[Singapore]] as looking for pilots so that was where he would go. VNAF Pilots started talking about stealing planes with their families so command ordered to fuel the aircraft only with enough to complete their missions. This created a major problem for Khiem. Another was finding someone to help a family escape.\u00a0 \n\n=== Preparation ===\nOne of Khiem's close friends was Major Nguyen Canh in the [[VNAF|South Vietnam Air Force]] and he was in Khiem's sister squadron the 437th Squadron. They discussed the escape and Khiem told him they must be the first otherwise there wouldn't be a second. Major Canh's family was in [[Da Lat]], and he wanted to get them to Saigon before leaving.\u00a0 On 2 April, Da Lat was overrun by the communists and Nguyen lost contact with them.\u00a0After that, he was prepared to escape. On 3 April, all the C-130s were used on bombing missions and Khiem was number one standby for the mission planning board, but Khiem needed to tell his family his plan to escape.\u00a0Khiem went to the Squadron Ops telling the Officer he didn't feel good, and he agreed to drop Khiem to the bottom of the list.\u00a0 This gave Khiem time to run home to tell one of his brothers what he had planned.\u00a0Khiem told his brother to make sure his family close to home because they were all gathered in Saigon.  Khiem told his family to rush to the [[Long Thanh Airport]] as soon as they heard from him. [[Bearcat Base|Long Thanh]] was originally a US Army airbase that Khiem had landed many times in training.\u00a0It was closed and deserted since the US withdrawal in 1973. \n[[File:Pham_Quang_Khiem_in_C-130A.jpg|alt=|thumb|27-year-old Pham Quang Khiem in C-130A: 1974]]\nKhiem's house was in a mile of the airport and ran home and told his family to leave.\u00a0But there was a hindrance, Khiem and Nguyen were in different squadrons, and would not usually fly together\u00a0and could not even get into the squadron area because the guards were unfamiliar with him. But luck was on Khiem's side. The airplane Khiem was supposed to escape with had mechanical problems, and the 437th had to borrow the 435th's C-130a HCF 460, nickname \"''Saigon Lady''\", and would let Khiem in the area. Now Khiem\u00a0had to get rid of Canh's co-pilot. The co-pilot let Khiem fly gladly cause he wanted the rest of the day off to prepare for his date.\n\nNow the biggest problem left of all: the fuel. Khiem thought they would only have enough fuel to maybe make it to Thailand. Khiem quickly checked the fuel to find out the entire tank was full. The man fueling the tank took a smoke break and filled the tank all the way. This full tank of gas meant Singapore was possible. \n\nLt. Khiem, Major Canh, and the rest of the crew (not knowing where they were going) were prepared for takeoff. Khiem took off without clearance and turned southeast instead of east. Khiem told the crew on the intercom that they were redirected to Long Thanh instead of [[Phan Rang Air Base|Phan Rang]]. They landed safely land the loadmaster opened the ramp unloading 20,000 lbs of dry-rice. Khiem's brother in [[Phan Rang Air Base|Phan Rang]] made it to their parent's house in Saigon a few minutes before the escape. While Khiem's family and friends of 53 people boarded, he told the crew that he was escaping Vietnam and they could come if they wanted. The Flight Engineer got up then sat back down and said he would come. The number one loadmaster thought Khiem and Canh were defecting to the North Vietnamese.\u00a0He served in the VNAF for ten years and ran away as fast as he could. The other loadmaster was on his first C-130 training ride and had no clue as to what was going on, so he just stood next to the open ramp.\n\n=== Escape ===\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://welovedexter.com/2018/09/02/phillip-phams-father-borrows-military-plane-saves-family/|title=Phillip Pham\u2019s Father \u201cBorrows\u201d Military Plane, Saves Family|last=Communities|first=Disover|date=2 September 2019|website=We Love Dexter|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> Khiem started taxiing away but when everyone boarded the plane with their luggage, Khiem's two-year-old daughter was trampled and knocked out with blood everywhere. Khiem's wife, Ngoc-My, saw her thinking she was dead and passed out dropping their infant child on the ground. The infant child was left on the tarmac as Khiem started to taxi but, luckily, Khiem's oldest brother's wife ran out and grabbed the infant and ran back into the moving C-130A (all of them recovered after). As Khiem started taxiing to the takeoff end of the runway, Khiem saw the loadmaster speaking to many [[Army of the Republic of Vietnam|ARVN]] soldiers who came in a jeep. As Khiem and Canh turned to take off, the Jeep came and pointed an [[M79 grenade launcher|M-79 grenade launcher]] at the cockpit. Khiem\u00a0took off anyways knowing they wouldn't fire.  The ramp was still open, so Khiem ran back and told the puzzled, inexperienced loadmaster to hold the switch until the ramp was up, then Khiem ran to the cockpit\u00a0just in time to raise the gear. The\u00a0period from Khiem landing to Khiem and the passengers leaving was only seven minutes.\n\n==== Shallow Flying ====\nKhiem and Canh flew at tree-top level until they reached the sea then they dropped down to the sea-level. it got very humid in the back resulting in a thick fog forming. Khiem's family and friends could not see each other because the fog was too thick. One hour later, they raised to 16,000 feet and flew straight to Singapore.\u00a0\n\n==== Singapore ====\n[[File:Picture_of_a_C-130A_of_the_VNAF.jpg|alt=|thumb|One of the C-130A's Khiem flew in the VNAF]]\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thekopi.co/2020/01/24/refugees-c-130-plane/|title=How Vietnam War Refugees Fled to Singapore Using a Stolen C-130 Plane|last=Ng|first=Vanessa|date=2019|website=The Kopi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> They arrived in Singapore at around 7:00 PM. Khiem called Approach Control for instructions but could not understand them, so he changed to Tower Frequency, and requested\u00a0landing instruction. Yet, the call was intercepted by the [[Republic of Singapore Air Force|Singapore Air Force]]. Khiem told the other end of the line that the C-130A was off course and running out of fuel. So, they allowed Khiem to land on runway 02. They all stayed put until the authorities came.\n\nThe officials had no clue what to do with them. Singapore Prime Minister [[Lee Kuan Yew]] was out of the country for another two weeks. The Singapore Air Defense Command (SADC) was also renamed the Republic of Singapore Air Force (RSAF) on 01 April 1975, just two days before Khiem arrived. \n\nKhiem proposed for them to leave Singapore and go to Australia so Singapore wouldn't have to deal with them. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://raiderrelease.com/1343/features/mr-pham-shares-experience-of-escaping-communist-invasion-of-south-viet-nam/|title=Mr. Pham Shares Experience of Escaping Communist Invasion of South Viet Nam|last=Klegg|first=Kassandra|date=March 3, 2015|website=Raider Release|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>They agreed, but only if they would pay for gas. They only accepted U.S. currency and all the passengers had a combined total of around $100-400. Khiem tried to bribe with jewelry but they would not accept. The group was moved in separate prison trucks to a detention center outside Singapore. Khiem and the others were released until the [[Fall of Saigon]]. \n\n==== Saipan ====\nAfter spending three weeks in the jail, they were all flown to [[Saipan]] in a deluxe hotel. After a week there, they finally learned that the [[South Vietnam|Republic of Vietnam]] (South Vietnam) had fallen to the northern communists.\n\n==== The United States of America ====\nKhiem and his family ended up at [[Marine Corps Base Camp Pendleton|Camp Pendleton, California]], where they were processed into the U.S. Finally, Khiem, Canh, and the others were free at last.\n\n== Homecoming ==\nKhiem got his entire family out, except his youngest brother in the [[Army of the Republic of Vietnam|ARVN]]. He was stationed at [[V\u0169ng T\u00e0u]]. After the communists took over, he was sent to a brain-washing camp for two years. On 01 August 1992, he was reunited with Khiem and his family through the [[Orderly Departure Program|ODP program]].\n\n== Post-Vietnam Career ==\nWhen Captain Mastronardi found out Khiem was in America, he sent Khiem $500 ($2,200+ today). Khiem and his family then settled in [[Dayton, Ohio]], birthplace of flight, and home to [[Wright-Patterson Air Force Base|Wright-Patterson AFB]]. In the mid 80's, Khiem was hired by [[Piedmont Airlines (1948\u20131989)|Piedmont Airlines]], (later merged with [[US Airways|USAir]] and now [[American Airlines|US Airways]]) and moved to the right seat in only 3 years later. \n\n=== Kind of Hard Landing ===\nOn January 30, 1991, Khiem was flying a [[Boeing 737]], and after leaving [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh NC]], he headed up to [[Washington National Airport]]. Khiem was ready to land at runway 36 but when he was about 3 miles from it, the plane taking off that runway aborted making Khiem redirect to runway 33 (a shorter runway). Khiem swung over, aligning with runway 33 and prepared land. Runway 33 was even shorter with the [[Potomac River]] on one end and [[The Pentagon]] on the other. Khiem maintained airspeed and tried to touch down on the runway numbers which are only 500 feet from the end of runway instead of 1000 feet and Khiem let the air speed drop 5 knots. The 737 slammed on the runway with the two main wheels and the nose with 87 people on-board. Khiem knew this landing was a bit hard on the passengers and was the only bad landing he made in his airline pilot career.\n\n== ''Saigon Lady'' ==\n[[File:Pham_Family_Reunited_With_Saigon_Lady_after_10_years.jpg|alt=|left|thumb|Khiem Pham and his Family Reunited With Saigon Lady after 10 years.]]\n[[File:\"Saigon_Lady\",_C-130A_at_National_Warplane_Musuem.jpg|link=File:%22Saigon_Lady%22,_C-130A_at_National_Warplane_Musuem.jpg|alt=|thumb|\"Saigon Lady\", C-130A at National Warplane Musuem]]\nOn April 19, 1985, Khiem and his family visited [[Selfridge Air National Guard Base|Selfridge AFB]] to see the plane that brought his family freedom after ten years. \n\n''Saigon Lady'' was transferred to the [[National Air and Space Museum|Smithsonian National Air and Space Museum]] on January 30, 1989, where it has been until it was transferred to the [[National Warplane Museum]] for restoration and preparation for public display.\n<br />\n[[File:\"Saigon_Lady\"_in_Washington.jpg|link=File:%22Saigon_Lady%22_in_Washington.jpg|alt=|center|thumb|C-130A, \"Saigon Lady\" in Washington]]\n\n\n\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. --><references />\n[[Category:Vietnam War]]\n[[Category:Military personnel of the Vietnam War]]\n{{Uncategorised|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "<!-- Important, do not remove this line before article has been created. -->\n{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Pham Quang Khiem\n| image         = KhiemQPham.jpg\n| caption       = Lt. Pham Q. Khiem, was pilot of C-130A \"Saigon Lady\"\n| birth_date    = December 27, 1946\n| birth_place   = V\u0129nh-Long, Vietnam\n| allegiance    = {{flag|South Vietnam}}\n| branch        = {{Air force|South Vietnam}}\n| serviceyears  = 1969-1975\n| rank          = First Lieutenant\n| unit          = 435th Transport Squadron\n| battles       = Vietnam War\n| spouse        = Ngoc-My Tran (m. 1972)\n| children      = 3\n| laterwork     = Airline Pilot\n}}\n\nPham Quang Khiem (born December 27, 1946) was a First Lieutenant and Co-Pilot in the [[South Vietnam Air Force]] (VNAF) during the [[Vietnam War]]. Khiem was a cargo pilot with the 53rd Tactical Wing of the 5th Air Division stationed at [[Tan Son Nhut Air Base|Tan Son Nhut]]. Khiem flew several missions into communists gained [[Pleiku Air Base|Pleiku]] in hopes to rescue VNAF personnel. On 03 April 1975, Khiem organized a plan to steal a C-130a and gather 53 people to rescue them from the communist [[North Vietnam|North Vietnamese]]. Later, Khiem became a pilot for [[Piedmont Airlines (1948\u20131989)|Piedmont Airlines]] until 2006.\n\n== Early Life ==\n[[File:Pham_Family_1960.jpg|alt=|left|thumb|190x190px|Pham family in 1960.]]\nPham Quang Khiem was born on December 27, 1946, in [[V\u0129nh Long|V\u0129nh-Long, Vietnam]]. Khiem had ten siblings (five boys and five girls) and all of his brothers were in the military. Three of them were in the VNAF and one in the [[Army of the Republic of Vietnam|ARVN]]. Khiem got married on June 8, 1972, to Ngoc-My Tran. Together they had three children: two in South Vietnam and one in the [[United States|United States of America]].\n\n== Early Career ==\n[[File:Pham_Quang_Khiem_at_Lockbourne_AFB.jpg|alt=|left|thumb|195x195px|Pham Quang Khiem at Lockbourne AFB]]\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://t28trojanfoundation.com/vnaf.html|title=VNAF|website=Helen Murphy|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>In November 1969, Khiem went to [[Lackland Air Force Base|Lackland AFB]] to learn [[English language|English]] as a VNAF air cadet. At [[Randolph Air Force Base|Randolph AFB]], he earned his basic pilot training, then moved on to [[Keesler Air Force Base|Keesler AFB]], where he flew the [[T-28 Trojan]].\u00a0Khiem also trained at [[Lockbourne AFB]] from October-December of 1970. Eventually, he was designated to fly transport aircraft and was pilot-in-command of [[C-123K]] aircraft before moving up to the 53rd Tactical Wing, 435th Transport Squadron as a [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules|C-130A]] pilot. \n\n\n\n\n=== Hard Landing ===\n[[File:PQK Tough Landing.jpg|thumb|Pham Quang Khiem in front of the C-123K after the crash landing]]\nOn January 24, 1971, Pham Quang Khiem nearly died almost ending his flight career before it started.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vnafmamn.com/hall-offame/amazing_story.html|title=VNAF \"amazing story\"|website=vnafmamn.com|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> After a year of training in the states, Khiem's group was sent to [[Phan Rang Air Base|Phan-Rang AFB]] by the VNAF to start \"In Country Training\" with the [[United States Air Force|USAF]] on a [[C-123K]]. Khiem was assigned to fly with 1LT. Minh and their American Instructor, Cpt. John Mastronardi. Minh was the Aircraft Commander in the left seat and in the right, Khiem switched with Captain Mastronardi to execute co-pilot duties. One day, they had an assignment to transfer 48 of 175-millimeter high explosive bullet heads from [[Bien Hoa Air Base|Bien-Hoa Air Base]] to a US firebase 113 kilometers north near the [[Cambodia|Cambodian]] border. They had to land into an isolated area for a safe distance from any airport facilities since they carried high explosive material. They landed on the short dirt strip, [[B\u00f9 Gia M\u1eadp District|B\u00f9 Gia M\u1eadp]] Air Strip (aka Djamap). The runway was 3000' on top of a 1620' hill. Co-Pilots (in this training) weren't allowed to make any landing on any runway shorter than 3600'. Minh was supposed to handle this flight, but Captain Mastronardi kept Khiem in the right seat believing he could handle the landing after previous successful landings. Khiem was a young pilot and didn't know the difference between a short runway and a long one. It was a hostile area so they had to come in high and drop fast. They came down to 2000' at 78 knots and when the [[C-123K]] was about 20 feet in the air crossing the end of the runway Khiem decided to cut the power to idle causing the aircraft to drop touching down extremely hard. The left main landing gear fell into the belly wrecking the wheel and scratched all the red dirt on the runway skyrocketing it into the cockpit. Khiem and Minh couldn't see anything in front of them. Captain Mastronardi immediately reversed the right engine, bringing the aircraft back stopping the aircraft. If Captain Mastronardi had not stop the aircraft, the whole aircraft may have run off the dirt strip dropping hundreds of yards exploding on the side of the hill.\n\n== End of the War ==\nAt the end of March 1975, the North Vietnamese had already taken half of South Vietnam. Citizens were fleeing as well as soldiers creating chaos throughout the country. Both civilians and officers were hitching military aircraft to escape the North Vietnamese. At the end of March of 1975, the [[North Vietnamese army|NVA]] was pushing towards the coast to strike [[Qui Nh\u01a1n]], [[Tuy H\u00f2a]], and [[Nha Trang]]. \n\n=== Pleiku ===\n[[File:North Vietnamese Gains in the last week of March of '75.jpg|thumb|249x249px|North Vietnamese Gains in the last week of March of '75]]\n<ref>{{Cite book|last=Snepp|first=Frank|title=Decent Interval|publisher=Random House|year=1977|isbn=0-394-40743-1|location=New York, United States|pages=234}}</ref> In the north of South Vietnam, the only remaining government enclave was [[Da Nang]]. <ref>{{Cite book|last=Drendel|first=Lou|title=Air War over Southeast Asia|publisher=squadron/signal|year=1984|isbn=0-89747-148-2|location=1115 Crowley Dr., Carrolton, TX|pages=65}}</ref> Khiem flew three missions into and out of [[Pleiku]], evacuating the families of VNAF personnel. The civil population of Pleiku learned of the evacuation and stormed the [[Pleiku Air Base|airport]]. This forced five C-130's en route from Saigon to turn around before their airlifts were complete. Some C-130's flew bombing missions to destroy the aircraft left behind. They were loaded with 55-gallon drums of [[napalm]], then dropped on VNAF aircraft abandoned on the ramps.\n\n=== Da Nang ===\n28 March 1975, Khiem flew one of the last missions to [[Da Nang Air Base|Da Nang]] at 11:00 PM, the night before it's loss. When he landed and taxied to the ramp, an [[Army of the Republic of Vietnam|ARVN]] major jumped into the aircraft to assure himself of a seat. Khiem knew that the thousands of people in the terminal would rush the airplane after seeing this, so Khiem kicked him off. Khiem was a First Lieutenant, and the aircraft commander was searching the terminal for his family. But, the ramp was filled with refugees almost immediately anyway. Around 20,000 pounds of cargo on board, so Khiem yelled at them to offload first. The crowd was too chaotic, so Khiem told the [[loadmaster]] to do unloading and loading through the ramp in the back of the C-130. Once finished, people rushed onto the aircraft. Khiem started the engines, scattering many, allowing Khiem to taxi out.\n\nAs they taxied, the loadmaster yelled at Khiem through the intercom saying he couldn't close the ramp because people were on it. Khiem hit the brakes jamming the refugees in tight allowing the ramp to close. At the end of the runway, an MP (Military Police) in a truck had his family in it, blocking the taxiway and pointing his M-16 at the cockpit.  He motioned to let his family on board. Khiem motioned him to move the truck so he could line up on the runway. Khiem backed up, lined up and took off without the MP. Khiem offloaded at [[Tan Son Nhut Air Base|Tan Son Nhut]] and did a headcount of 350 people. C-130's are maximized to carry 92 passengers but Khiem fit almost four times that amount. \n\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://airandspace.si.edu/collection-objects/lockheed-c-130a-45-lm-hercules|title=Lockheed C-130a 45 lm Hercules|last=|first=|date=|website=Smithsonian National Air and Space Musuem|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=7 April 2020|quote=\"That flight and the panic that Lt. Khiem saw in Da Nang caused him to consider that if this was likely to happen in Saigon, he would steal a C-130 and get his own family out.\"}}</ref>That mission was the turning point for Khiem. He knew if the chaos reaches Saigon he had to get his family out of Vietnam for good.\n\n=== Nha Trang ===\n31 March 1975, Khiem flew several missions in the evacuation of [[Nha Trang]]. The following day [[Qui Nh\u01a1n]], South Vietnam's third-largest city was captured by the North Vietnamese. The next target for the North Vietnamese was [[Nha Trang Air Base|Nha Trang]]. Khiem just made it just like he did in Da Nang.\n\n== Flight To Freedom ==\n2 April 1975, Khiem caught a ride on a C-130 \"bladder bird\" into [[Phan Rang Air Base|Phan Rang]], in hopes to pinpoint his younger brother, who was an airman there.\u00a0Khiem wanted to take him back to [[Saigon]] to be with the rest of their family.\u00a0Khiem couldn't find hi, so left without him. On the way back to Saigon, Khiem thought if Phan Rang is lost, then\u00a0the communists will come to Saigon. Khiem started to devise a plan to escape South Vietnam with his family. Khiem heard that [[Singapore]] as looking for pilots so that was where he would go. VNAF Pilots started talking about stealing planes with their families so command ordered to fuel the aircraft only with enough to complete their missions. This created a major problem for Khiem. Another was finding someone to help a family escape.\u00a0 \n\n=== Preparation ===\nOne of Khiem's close friends was Major Nguyen Canh in the [[VNAF|South Vietnam Air Force]] and he was in Khiem's sister squadron the 437th Squadron. They discussed the escape and Khiem told him they must be the first otherwise there wouldn't be a second. Major Canh's family was in [[Da Lat]], and he wanted to get them to Saigon before leaving.\u00a0 On 2 April, Da Lat was overrun by the communists and Nguyen lost contact with them.\u00a0After that, he was prepared to escape. On 3 April, all the C-130s were used on bombing missions and Khiem was number one standby for the mission planning board, but Khiem needed to tell his family his plan to escape.\u00a0Khiem went to the Squadron Ops telling the Officer he didn't feel good, and he agreed to drop Khiem to the bottom of the list.\u00a0 This gave Khiem time to run home to tell one of his brothers what he had planned.\u00a0Khiem told his brother to make sure his family close to home because they were all gathered in Saigon.  Khiem told his family to rush to the [[Long Thanh Airport]] as soon as they heard from him. [[Bearcat Base|Long Thanh]] was originally a US Army airbase that Khiem had landed many times in training.\u00a0It was closed and deserted since the US withdrawal in 1973. \n[[File:Pham_Quang_Khiem_in_C-130A.jpg|alt=|thumb|27-year-old Pham Quang Khiem in C-130A: 1974]]\nKhiem's house was in a mile of the airport and ran home and told his family to leave.\u00a0But there was a hindrance, Khiem and Nguyen were in different squadrons, and would not usually fly together\u00a0and could not even get into the squadron area because the guards were unfamiliar with him. But luck was on Khiem's side. The airplane Khiem was supposed to escape with had mechanical problems, and the 437th had to borrow the 435th's C-130a HCF 460, nickname \"''Saigon Lady''\", and would let Khiem in the area. Now Khiem\u00a0had to get rid of Canh's co-pilot. The co-pilot let Khiem fly gladly cause he wanted the rest of the day off to prepare for his date.\n\nNow the biggest problem left of all: the fuel. Khiem thought they would only have enough fuel to maybe make it to Thailand. Khiem quickly checked the fuel to find out the entire tank was full. The man fueling the tank took a smoke break and filled the tank all the way. This full tank of gas meant Singapore was possible. \n\nLt. Khiem, Major Canh, and the rest of the crew (not knowing where they were going) were prepared for takeoff. Khiem took off without clearance and turned southeast instead of east. Khiem told the crew on the intercom that they were redirected to Long Thanh instead of [[Phan Rang Air Base|Phan Rang]]. They landed safelyand the loadmaster opened the ramp unloading 20,000 lbs of dry-rice. Khiem's brother in [[Phan Rang Air Base|Phan Rang]] made it to their parent's house in Saigon a few minutes before the escape. While Khiem's family and friends of 53 people boarded, he told the crew that he was escaping Vietnam and they could come if they wanted. The Flight Engineer got up then sat back down and said he would come. The number one loadmaster thought Khiem and Canh were defecting to the North Vietnamese.\u00a0He served in the VNAF for ten years and ran away as fast as he could. The other loadmaster was on his first C-130 training ride and had no clue as to what was going on, so he just stood next to the open ramp.\n\n=== Escape ===\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://welovedexter.com/2018/09/02/phillip-phams-father-borrows-military-plane-saves-family/|title=Phillip Pham\u2019s Father \u201cBorrows\u201d Military Plane, Saves Family|last=Communities|first=Disover|date=2 September 2019|website=We Love Dexter|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> Khiem started taxiing away but when everyone boarded the plane with their luggage, Khiem's two-year-old daughter was trampled and knocked out with blood everywhere. Khiem's wife, Ngoc-My, saw her thinking she was dead and passed out dropping their infant child on the ground. The infant child was left on the tarmac as Khiem started to taxi but, luckily, Khiem's oldest brother's wife ran out and grabbed the infant and ran back into the moving C-130A (all of them recovered after). As Khiem started taxiing to the takeoff end of the runway, Khiem saw the loadmaster speaking to many [[Army of the Republic of Vietnam|ARVN]] soldiers who came in a jeep. As Khiem and Canh turned to take off, the Jeep came and pointed an [[M79 grenade launcher|M-79 grenade launcher]] at the cockpit. Khiem\u00a0took off anyways knowing they wouldn't fire.  The ramp was still open, so Khiem ran back and told the puzzled, inexperienced loadmaster to hold the switch until the ramp was up, then Khiem ran to the cockpit\u00a0just in time to raise the gear. The\u00a0period from Khiem landing to Khiem and the passengers leaving was only seven minutes.\n\n==== Shallow Flying ====\nKhiem and Canh flew at tree-top level until they reached the sea then they dropped down to the sea-level. it got very humid in the back resulting in a thick fog forming. Khiem's family and friends could not see each other because the fog was too thick. One hour later, they raised to 16,000 feet and flew straight to Singapore.\u00a0\n\n==== Singapore ====\n[[File:Picture_of_a_C-130A_of_the_VNAF.jpg|alt=|thumb|One of the C-130A's Khiem flew in the VNAF]]\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thekopi.co/2020/01/24/refugees-c-130-plane/|title=How Vietnam War Refugees Fled to Singapore Using a Stolen C-130 Plane|last=Ng|first=Vanessa|date=2019|website=The Kopi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> They arrived in Singapore at around 7:00 PM. Khiem called Approach Control for instructions but could not understand them, so he changed to Tower Frequency, and requested\u00a0landing instruction. Yet, the call was intercepted by the [[Republic of Singapore Air Force|Singapore Air Force]]. Khiem told the other end of the line that the C-130A was off course and running out of fuel. So, they allowed Khiem to land on runway 02. They all stayed put until the authorities came.\n\nThe officials had no clue what to do with them. Singapore Prime Minister [[Lee Kuan Yew]] was out of the country for another two weeks. The Singapore Air Defense Command (SADC) was also renamed the Republic of Singapore Air Force (RSAF) on 01 April 1975, just two days before Khiem arrived. \n\nKhiem proposed for them to leave Singapore and go to Australia so Singapore wouldn't have to deal with them. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://raiderrelease.com/1343/features/mr-pham-shares-experience-of-escaping-communist-invasion-of-south-viet-nam/|title=Mr. Pham Shares Experience of Escaping Communist Invasion of South Viet Nam|last=Klegg|first=Kassandra|date=March 3, 2015|website=Raider Release|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>They agreed, but only if they would pay for gas. They only accepted U.S. currency and all the passengers had a combined total of around $100-400. Khiem tried to bribe with jewelry but they would not accept. The group was moved in separate prison trucks to a detention center outside Singapore. Khiem and the others were released until the [[Fall of Saigon]]. \n\n==== Saipan ====\nAfter spending three weeks in the jail, they were all flown to [[Saipan]] in a deluxe hotel. After a week there, they finally learned that the [[South Vietnam|Republic of Vietnam]] (South Vietnam) had fallen to the northern communists.\n\n==== The United States of America ====\nKhiem and his family ended up at [[Marine Corps Base Camp Pendleton|Camp Pendleton, California]], where they were processed into the U.S. Finally, Khiem, Canh, and the others were free at last.\n\n== Homecoming ==\nKhiem got his entire family out, except his youngest brother in the [[Army of the Republic of Vietnam|ARVN]]. He was stationed at [[V\u0169ng T\u00e0u]]. After the communists took over, he was sent to a brain-washing camp for two years. On 01 August 1992, he was reunited with Khiem and his family through the [[Orderly Departure Program|ODP program]].\n\n== Post-Vietnam Career ==\nWhen Captain Mastronardi found out Khiem was in America, he sent Khiem $500 ($2,200+ today). Khiem and his family then settled in [[Dayton, Ohio]], birthplace of flight, and home to [[Wright-Patterson Air Force Base|Wright-Patterson AFB]]. In the mid 80's, Khiem was hired by [[Piedmont Airlines (1948\u20131989)|Piedmont Airlines]], (later merged with [[US Airways|USAir]] and now [[American Airlines|US Airways]]) and moved to the right seat in only 3 years later. \n\n=== Kind of Hard Landing ===\nOn January 30, 1991, Khiem was flying a [[Boeing 737]], and after leaving [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh NC]], he headed up to [[Washington National Airport]]. Khiem was ready to land at runway 36 but when he was about 3 miles from it, the plane taking off that runway aborted making Khiem redirect to runway 33 (a shorter runway). Khiem swung over, aligning with runway 33 and prepared land. Runway 33 was even shorter with the [[Potomac River]] on one end and [[The Pentagon]] on the other. Khiem maintained airspeed and tried to touch down on the runway numbers which are only 500 feet from the end of runway instead of 1000 feet and Khiem let the air speed drop 5 knots. The 737 slammed on the runway with the two main wheels and the nose with 87 people on-board. Khiem knew this landing was a bit hard on the passengers and was the only bad landing he made in his airline pilot career.\n\n== ''Saigon Lady'' ==\n[[File:Pham_Family_Reunited_With_Saigon_Lady_after_10_years.jpg|alt=|left|thumb|Khiem Pham and his Family Reunited With Saigon Lady after 10 years.]]\n[[File:\"Saigon_Lady\",_C-130A_at_National_Warplane_Musuem.jpg|link=File:%22Saigon_Lady%22,_C-130A_at_National_Warplane_Musuem.jpg|alt=|thumb|\"Saigon Lady\", C-130A at National Warplane Musuem]]\nOn April 19, 1985, Khiem and his family visited [[Selfridge Air National Guard Base|Selfridge AFB]] to see the plane that brought his family freedom after ten years. \n\n''Saigon Lady'' was transferred to the [[National Air and Space Museum|Smithsonian National Air and Space Museum]] on January 30, 1989, where it has been until it was transferred to the [[National Warplane Museum]] for restoration and preparation for public display.\n<br />\n[[File:\"Saigon_Lady\"_in_Washington.jpg|link=File:%22Saigon_Lady%22_in_Washington.jpg|alt=|center|thumb|C-130A, \"Saigon Lady\" in Washington]]\n\n\n\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. --><references />\n[[Category:Vietnam War]]\n[[Category:Military personnel of the Vietnam War]]\n{{Uncategorised|date=April 2020}}\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "typos", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pham_Quang_Khiem"}
{"title_page": "Raven", "text_new": "{{short description|Several species of the genus Corvus}}\n{{other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n[[File:3782 Common Raven in flight.jpg|thumb|right|A raven in flight]]\nA '''raven''' is one of several larger-bodied species of the [[genus]] ''[[Corvus]]''. These species do not form a single [[Taxon|taxonomic group]] within the genus.\n\nThere is no consistent distinction between \"[[crow]]s\" and \"ravens\", and these appellations have been assigned to different species chiefly on the basis of their size, crows generally being smaller than ravens.\n\nThe largest raven species are the [[common raven]] and the [[thick-billed raven]].\n\n==Etymology==\nThe term \"raven\" originally referred to the [[common raven]] (''Corvus corax''), the type species of the genus ''Corvus'', which has a larger distribution than any other species of ''Corvus'', ranging over much of the [[Northern Hemisphere]].\n\nThe modern English word ''raven'' has cognates in all other [[Germanic languages]], including [[Old Norse]] (and subsequently [[Icelandic language|modern Icelandic]]) ''hrafn''<ref>''Oxford English Dictionary'' entry for \"raven.\"</ref> and [[Old High German]] ''(h)raban'',<ref>{{Cite encyclopedia| title=Raven|encyclopedia=Oxford English Dictionary|editor=Simpson, J. |editor2=Weiner, E. | year=1989 |edition= 2nd| location=Oxford |publisher=Clarendon Press|isbn= 0-19-861186-2}}</ref> all of which descend from [[Proto-Germanic]] ''*hrabanaz''.<ref>{{cite web| title=Raven| work=Online Etymology Dictionary| url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=raven| accessdate=14 May 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[Collective noun]]s for a group of ravens (or at least the common raven) include \"unkindness\",<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lipton|first=James|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AVNazQEACAAJ&newbks=0&hl=en|title=An Exaltation of Larks|date=1991|publisher=Viking|isbn=978-0-670-30044-0|language=en}}</ref> \"treachery\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://baltimorebirdclub.org/gnlist.html | title=Baltimore Bird Club. Group Name for Birds: A Partial List | accessdate=3 June 2007}}</ref> and \"conspiracy\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucgc.org/terms-for-collections.htm | title=University of California Golf Club. List of Collective Nouns | accessdate=16 July 2008}}</ref> In practice, most people use the more generic \"flock\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/ngrams/graph?content=flock+of+ravens,unkindness+of+ravens,treachery+of+ravens,conspiracy+of+ravens&year_start=1900&year_end=2008&corpus=15&smoothing=3&share=&direct_url=t1%3B%2Cflock%20of%20ravens%3B%2Cc0%3B.t1%3B%2Cunkindness%20of%20ravens%3B%2Cc0t1;,flock%20of%20ravens;,c0;.t1;,unkindness%20of%20ravens;,c0|title=Google Ngram Viewer|website=books.google.com|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref>\n\n==Current species==\n* ''[[Corvus albicollis]]'' \u2013 [[white-necked raven]] (eastern and southern Africa)\n* ''[[Corvus corax]]'' \u2013 [[common raven]] (northern hemisphere)\n* ''[[Corvus coronoides]]'' \u2013 [[Australian raven]] (Australia)\n* ''[[Corvus crassirostris]]'' \u2013 [[thick-billed raven]] (Horn of Africa)\n* ''[[Corvus cryptoleucus]]'' \u2013 [[Chihuahuan raven]] (United States and Mexico)\n* ''[[Corvus mellori]]'' \u2013 [[little raven]] (southeastern Australia)\n* ''[[Corvus rhipidurus]]'' \u2013 [[fan-tailed raven]] (eastern Africa and Arabian peninsula)\n* ''[[Corvus ruficollis]]'' \u2013 [[brown-necked raven]] (northern Africa, Arabian peninusla, Greater Middle East)\n* ''[[Corvus tasmanicus]]'' \u2013 [[forest raven]] (Tasmania, southern Victoria and north-east NSW in Australia)\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Head of Raven.jpg|Head of a [[common raven]]\nFile:Corvus corax jouveniles.jpeg|Common ravens\nFile:Corvus cryptoleucus Arizona 2.jpg|[[Chihuahuan raven]]\nFile:Fan-tailed raven.jpg|[[Fan-tailed raven]]\nFile:Australian Raven Sydney University.jpg|[[Australian raven]]\nFile:Ravaged Raven in Flight.jpg|Ravaged wing of combative Raven, still allows it to fly with ease\n</gallery>\n\n==Extinct species==\n* \u2020''[[Corvus moriorum]]'' \u2013 [[Chatham raven]]\n* \u2020''[[Corvus antipodum]]'' \u2013 [[New Zealand raven]]\n* \u2020''[[Corvus they have corona and are excint\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nphaeus]]'' \u2013 [[pied raven]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Cultural depictions of ravens]]\n* [[Ravens of the Tower of London]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|Ravens}}\n{{Wikisource1911Enc|Raven}}\n* [http://ibc.lynxeds.com/family/crows-corvidae Raven videos] on the Internet Bird Collection\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101229105854/http://enature.com/fieldguides/view_default.asp?allSpecies=y&searchText=raven North American ravens] on eNature\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DjRTeJduCKg Interesting raven video from Arizona] \n\n{{Animal common name}}\n\n[[Category:Birds by common name]]\n[[Category:Corvus (genus)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Several species of the genus Corvus}}\n{{other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n[[File:3782 Common Raven in flight.jpg|thumb|right|A raven in flight]]\nA '''raven''' is one of several larger-bodied species of the [[genus]] ''[[Corvus]]''. These species do not form a single [[Taxon|taxonomic group]] within the genus.\n\nThere is no consistent distinction between \"[[crow]]s\" and \"ravens\", and these appellations have been assigned to different species chiefly on the basis of their size, crows generally being smaller than ravens.\n\nThe largest raven species are the [[common raven]] and the [[thick-billed raven]].\n\n==Etymology==\nThe term \"raven\" originally referred to the [[common raven]] (''Corvus corax''), the type species of the genus ''Corvus'', which has a larger distribution than any other species of ''Corvus'', ranging over much of the [[Northern Hemisphere]].\n\nThe modern English word ''raven'' has cognates in all other [[Germanic languages]], including [[Old Norse]] (and subsequently [[Icelandic language|modern Icelandic]]) ''hrafn''<ref>''Oxford English Dictionary'' entry for \"raven.\"</ref> and [[Old High German]] ''(h)raban'',<ref>{{Cite encyclopedia| title=Raven|encyclopedia=Oxford English Dictionary|editor=Simpson, J. |editor2=Weiner, E. | year=1989 |edition= 2nd| location=Oxford |publisher=Clarendon Press|isbn= 0-19-861186-2}}</ref> all of which descend from [[Proto-Germanic]] ''*hrabanaz''.<ref>{{cite web| title=Raven| work=Online Etymology Dictionary| url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=raven| accessdate=14 May 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[Collective noun]]s for a group of ravens (or at least the common raven) include \"unkindness\",<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lipton|first=James|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AVNazQEACAAJ&newbks=0&hl=en|title=An Exaltation of Larks|date=1991|publisher=Viking|isbn=978-0-670-30044-0|language=en}}</ref> \"treachery\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://baltimorebirdclub.org/gnlist.html | title=Baltimore Bird Club. Group Name for Birds: A Partial List | accessdate=3 June 2007}}</ref> and \"conspiracy\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucgc.org/terms-for-collections.htm | title=University of California Golf Club. List of Collective Nouns | accessdate=16 July 2008}}</ref> In practice, most people use the more generic \"flock\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/ngrams/graph?content=flock+of+ravens,unkindness+of+ravens,treachery+of+ravens,conspiracy+of+ravens&year_start=1900&year_end=2008&corpus=15&smoothing=3&share=&direct_url=t1%3B%2Cflock%20of%20ravens%3B%2Cc0%3B.t1%3B%2Cunkindness%20of%20ravens%3B%2Cc0t1;,flock%20of%20ravens;,c0;.t1;,unkindness%20of%20ravens;,c0|title=Google Ngram Viewer|website=books.google.com|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref>\n\n==Current species==\n* ''[[Corvus albicollis]]'' \u2013 [[white-necked raven]] (eastern and southern Africa)\n* ''[[Corvus corax]]'' \u2013 [[common raven]] (northern hemisphere)\n* ''[[Corvus coronoides]]'' \u2013 [[Australian raven]] (Australia)\n* ''[[Corvus crassirostris]]'' \u2013 [[thick-billed raven]] (Horn of Africa)\n* ''[[Corvus cryptoleucus]]'' \u2013 [[Chihuahuan raven]] (United States and Mexico)\n* ''[[Corvus mellori]]'' \u2013 [[little raven]] (southeastern Australia)\n* ''[[Corvus rhipidurus]]'' \u2013 [[fan-tailed raven]] (eastern Africa and Arabian peninsula)\n* ''[[Corvus ruficollis]]'' \u2013 [[brown-necked raven]] (northern Africa, Arabian peninusla, Greater Middle East)\n* ''[[Corvus tasmanicus]]'' \u2013 [[forest raven]] (Tasmania, southern Victoria and north-east NSW in Australia)\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Head of Raven.jpg|Head of a [[common raven]]\nFile:Corvus corax jouveniles.jpeg|Common ravens\nFile:Corvus cryptoleucus Arizona 2.jpg|[[Chihuahuan raven]]\nFile:Fan-tailed raven.jpg|[[Fan-tailed raven]]\nFile:Australian Raven Sydney University.jpg|[[Australian raven]]\nFile:Ravaged Raven in Flight.jpg|Ravaged wing of combative Raven, still allows it to fly with ease\n</gallery>\n\n==Extinct species==\n* \u2020''[[Corvus moriorum]]'' \u2013 [[Chatham raven]]\n* \u2020''[[Corvus antipodum]]'' \u2013 [[New Zealand raven]]\n* \u2020''[[Corvus corax varius morpha leucophaeus]]'' \u2013 [[pied raven]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Cultural depictions of ravens]]\n* [[Ravens of the Tower of London]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|Ravens}}\n{{Wikisource1911Enc|Raven}}\n* [http://ibc.lynxeds.com/family/crows-corvidae Raven videos] on the Internet Bird Collection\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101229105854/http://enature.com/fieldguides/view_default.asp?allSpecies=y&searchText=raven North American ravens] on eNature\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DjRTeJduCKg Interesting raven video from Arizona] \n\n{{Animal common name}}\n\n[[Category:Birds by common name]]\n[[Category:Corvus (genus)]]\n", "name_user": "2601:150:4102:f020:411d:fa60:756e:e708", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eExtinct species)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Raven"}
{"title_page": "Hotter Than Fire", "text_new": "{{for|song by heavy metal band Racer X|Street Lethal}} \n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Hotter Than Fire\n| cover      = Eric-Saade-Dev-Hotter-Than-Fire.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Eric Saade]] featuring [[Dev (singer)|Dev]]\n| album      = [[Saade Vol. 2]]\n| released   = 2 November 2011\n| format     = [[CD single]], [[Digital distribution|digital download]]\n| recorded   = 2011<ref name=recorded />\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Europop]]|[[electropop]]}}\n| length     = 3:19<ref name=genre />\n| label      = [[Roxy Recordings]], [[All Around The World Productions]]\n| writer     = [[Eric Saade]], Jason Gill, [[J-Son]], [[Devin Tailes]]\n| producer   =\n| chronology = [[Eric Saade]]\n| prev_title = [[Hearts in the Air]]\n| prev_year  = 2011\n| next_title = [[Imagine (Tone Damli song)|Imagine]]\n| next_year  = 2012\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Dev (singer)|Dev]]\n | type       = single\n | prev_title = [[Hey Hey Hey (Pop Another Bottle)]]\n | prev_year  = 2011\n | title      = Hotter Than Fire\n | year       = 2011\n | next_title = [[Naked (Dev and Enrique Iglesias song)|Naked]]\n | next_year  = 2011\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Hotter Than Fire'''\" is a song by Swedish singer [[Eric Saade]] and American singer [[Dev (singer)|Dev]]. It is the first single from Saade's third album, ''[[Saade Vol. 2]]'', and was first released on 2 November 2011 in Sweden. The song reached #5 in Sweden.<ref name=charts />\n\n==Background==\n\"Hotter Than Fire\" was written by [[Eric Saade]], Jason Gill, [[Devin Tailes]], and [[J-Son]]. The song was recorded in 2011.<ref name=recorded />\n\nThe collaboration with [[Dev (singer)|Dev]] started after Saade saw the video of her single ''[[Bass Down Low]]''. Dev heard an early demo of ''Hotter Than Fire'' and said immediately yes after they asked her if she wanted to join the song. About the song and the collaboration with Dev, Saade said: \"It's a song that shows quite clearly where I am going. I love electro-pop and I feel like I'm in the middle of the development to begin to find what I want to do. When Dev wanted to sing on the song it became the icing on the cake. Her 'rap song' style was so perfect for the song. She made it sexy.\"\n\n==Other versions==\nRemixes of the song were released on 30 November 2011 in [[Sweden]].<ref name=remixes /> The remixes are from Niclas Kings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scandipop.co.uk/?p=8457|title=Scandipop.co.uk - Eric Saade: 'Hotter Than Fire' (Niclas Kings Remix)|date=2011-12-28|publisher=scandipop.co.uk|accessdate=2011-12-29}}</ref> A remixed version by LMC will be released as a single in the UK in 2012.\n\n==Critical reception==\n''Idolator'' wrote that the song is \"a blazing dance-pop jam\" and compared it to [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher]]'s \"[[DJ Got Us Fallin' in Love]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://idolator.com/6061062/eric-saade-dev-hotter-than-fire|title=Eric Saade And Dev Are \"Hotter Than Fire\" On New Single|date=2011-10-31|publisher=idolator.com|accessdate=2012-01-02}}</ref>\n==Music video==\nThe music video premiered on 7 December 2011. It was shot in one take and filmed on 19 November 2011 in [[Spain]], [[Sweden]] and the [[United Kingdom]]. [[Dev (singer)|Dev]] filmed her part in the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scandipop.co.uk/?p=8238|title=Scandipop.co.uk - Eric Saade's 'Hotter Than Fire' video!|date=2011-12-07|publisher=scandipop.co.uk|accessdate=2012-01-01}}</ref>\n\n== Chart positions ==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Chart (2011-2013)\n!Peak<br/>position\n|-\n{{single chart|Wallonia Tip|23|artist=Eric Saade feat. Dev|song=Hotter Than Fire|accessdate=8 January 2014|refname=\"Wallonia\"}}\n|-\n|Belgium ([[Ultratop]] Wallonia Dance)<ref name = \"Wallonia\"/>\n|align=center|48\n|-\n{{single chart|Sweden|5|artist=Eric Saade feat. Dev|song=Hotter Than Fire}}\n|}\n\n== Release history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Country\n! scope=\"col\"| Date\n! scope=\"col\"| Format\n! scope=\"col\"| Label\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Sweden\n| 2 November 2011\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[Compact Disc single|CD single]], [[Digital distribution|digital download]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[Roxy Recordings]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Sweden<ref name=remixes /> <small>(Remixes)</small>\n| 30 November 2011\n|-\n| United Kingdom<ref>[https://www.amazon.co.uk/Clubland-21-Various-Artists/dp/B0087C4KCC/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1341002742&sr=8-1]</ref>\n| 25 June 2012 (Only via [[Clubland (brand)|Clubland]] 21 Compilation Album)\n| All Around the World\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=genre>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/se/album/hotter-than-fire-feat.-dev/id476201172|title=iTunes - Music - Hotter Than Fire (feat. Dev) - Single by Eric Saade|website=iTunes Store|accessdate=2011-12-29}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=remixes>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/se/album/hotter-than-fire-remixes-single/id483569095|title=iTunes - Music - Hotter Than Fire (Remixes) - Single by Eric Saade|website=iTunes Store|accessdate=2011-12-29}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=charts>{{cite web|url=http://swedishcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Eric+Saade&titel=Saade+Vol.+2&cat=a|title=swedishcharts.com - Eric Saade - Saade Vol. 2|date=2011-12-09|website=swedishcharts.com|accessdate=2011-12-29}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=recorded>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicloversgroup.com/eric-saade-hotter-than-fire-lyrics-and-video/|title=Eric Saade - Hotter Than Fire Lyrics and Video|date=2011-11-06|publisher=musicloversgroup.com|accessdate=2012-01-08}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.ericsaade.com/ Eric Saade official website]\n*[http://www.facebook.com/EricSaadeOfficial?sk=wall Eric Saade official Facebook page]\n\n{{Eric Saade}}\n{{Dev}}\n\n[[Category:2011 singles]]\n[[Category:Eric Saade songs]]\n[[Category:Dev (singer) songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Jason Gill]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Eric Saade]]\